Plots_and_Analyses.R

jjudd5

2023-12-12

Introduction:

This file is going to contain the code and plots for the main analyses and figures/tables weve decided to make for the paper (as of 2/2/24). The code is currently being run on R/4.2.2

Packages:

Load the necessary data

This load and edits the necessary data file to do my analysis. This includes the cancer, PRS, and SES data for the 451 variant PRS and the 5 ancestries I have

data_raw = fread("/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Composite_DataFiles/composite_data_2024.05.16.csv")

# I also want to make sure to have new cancer variables that I can plug into my models. 
data_df = data_raw %>% 
  #First, I want a variable that counts any prostate cancer as case and no cancer at all as the control. 
  # If no prostate cancer, but other cancer, then that is NA
  mutate(prostate_case = ifelse(prostate == 1, 1,
                         ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                         ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                         ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0)))
                         )
                                 
         ) %>% 
  # I also want to include a measure of incident cancer
  mutate(prostate_incident = if_else(prostate_incid_any == 1, 1,
                                     if_else(prostate_incid_any == 0 & prostate == 1, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                                     ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0))))
                                     )
         ) %>% 
  # I also want prevalent cancer
  mutate(prostate_prevalent =  if_else(prostate_incid_any == 1, NA,
                                     if_else(prostate_incid_any == 0 & prostate == 1, 1,
                                     ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                                     ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0))))
                                     )
         ) %>% 
  # Make all of these factors
  mutate(prostate_case = as.factor(prostate_case),
         prostate_incident = as.factor(prostate_incident),
         prostate_prevalent = as.factor(prostate_prevalent)) %>% 
  # I want to remove non-UK assessment centers
  filter(Assessment_Centre %notin% c(11023, 11022, 11003, 11005, 11004)
  ) %>% 
  # I also want assessment center and the smoking to be a factor
  mutate(Assessment_Centre = as.factor(Assessment_Centre)) %>% 
  
  # And rename Townsend_Index to just Townsend for clarity
  rename(Townsend = Townsend_Index)

Code and Table generation

This next section is going to focus on the analyses/tables/figures/plots that will go into the paper

Table 1 - Descriptive Statistics

The first figure/table that I want will charactertize my data. THe main information I want from this table will include

  • Mean + SD for all the deprivation
  • Data for 4 genetics ancestries
  • Split across cases and controls
  • Separated on PSA Screening

SES Distribution

I first want to characterize the distribution of my cases/controls/prevalence across the different nSES/PRS quartiles.

# Remove non-relevant variables
keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances",
                   "table1") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# List to save results through section
table1 = list()

# Define a vector of standardized ses to call in order to calculate the mean
ses_standard = paste0(ses_factors, "_std")


# Pull the relevant variables that I'm trying to summarize. I want to standardize all the ses variables, so I'll do that now
split_prev = data_df %>% 
  select(Ances,
         contains( c("eid", "prostate_incident")), 
         PRS_z,
         no_visits,
         all_of(ses_factors)
         ) %>% 
  filter(Ances %in% ances ) %>% 
  group_by(Ances) %>% 
  mutate(across(ses_factors, ~ scale(.x)[,1] , .names = "{.col}_std"))

# I will now summarize this data to categorize case/controls as well as prevalence at the end. I AM CALCULATING THE MEAN/SD of the Standardized values
summ_df =  split_prev %>% 
  group_by(Ances, prostate_incident) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  # Summarize the mean and sd as desired
  summarize(across(c(ses_standard, "PRS_z"), 
                     ~ mean(.x, na.rm = TRUE), .names = "{.col}_mean"),
            across(c(ses_standard, "PRS_z"),
                   ~ sd(.x, na.rm = TRUE), .names = "{.col}_sd")
            ) %>% 
  mutate(across(ends_with("mean"),
                ~ format(round(.x, 2), nsmall = 2, scientific = FALSE)
                ),
        across(ends_with("sd"),
                ~ format(round(.x, 2), nsmall = 2, scientific = FALSE)
        )) %>% 
  # Pivot longer for clarity 
  pivot_longer(cols = contains("mean"), names_to = "Var_mean", values_to = "Mean") %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = contains("sd"), names_to = "Var_sd", values_to = "SD") %>% 
  # Organize slightly more for clarity
  mutate(Var_mean = str_split_i(Var_mean,"_", 1),
         Var_sd = str_split_i(Var_sd,"_", 1)) %>% 
  filter(Var_mean == Var_sd) %>% 
  select(-Var_sd) %>% rename(Index = Var_mean) %>% 
  
  # Now I want to pivot the data wider to enable me as a final clarity step
  pivot_wider(names_from = prostate_incident,
               names_sep = ".",
               values_from = c(Mean, SD)) %>% 
  
  # I want to combine the means and Sds for cases/controls
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ signif(., digits = 2))) %>% 
  mutate(Control = str_c(Mean.0, " (", SD.0, ")"),
         Case = str_c(Mean.1, " (", SD.1, ")")
         ) %>% 
  select(-c(Mean.0, Mean.1, SD.0, SD.1))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Ances'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.
# -- -- 
# I also want to calculate the median and iqr of the number of clinical visits variable so I will do that separately and then add on the original
summ_df_visits =  split_prev %>% 
  group_by(Ances, prostate_incident) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  # Summarize the mean and sd as desired
  summarize(visits_median = median(no_visits, na.rm = TRUE), 
            visits_25 = quantile(no_visits, 0.25),
            visits_75 = quantile(no_visits,0.75)
            ) %>% 
  # Combine the quantiles into a single iqr and remove the individual ones
  mutate(visits_iqr = paste0("(", visits_25, "-", visits_75, ")")) %>% 
  select(-visits_25,-visits_75) %>% 
  # Clarify the columns by having case/control columns
  pivot_wider(names_from = prostate_incident, 
              names_sep = ".",
              values_from = c(visits_median, visits_iqr)) %>% 
  # Now combine the median and iqr before removing the indiv. columns
  mutate(Control = str_c(visits_median.0, " ", visits_iqr.0),
         Case = str_c(visits_median.1, " ", visits_iqr.1)
         ) %>% 
  select(-c(visits_median.0, visits_iqr.0, visits_median.1, visits_iqr.1)
         )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Ances'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.

  # This is for formatting and easy understanding
  pivot_wider(names_from = prostate_incident,
              names_sep = ".",

  t() %>% as.data.frame()

PSA Distribution

Im also interested in the split of PSA screening for different SES groups for both cases and controls. I may not end up splitting the data by SES in the end, but that can be a later transofrmation

I largely just want the case/controls split for never/ever screened. I have code for quartile never/ever screened as well as screened in controls/cases over ses quartiles in previous iterations. I can redo that for a suppliment, but dont need it here.


# Remove non-relevant variables
keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances",
                   "table1") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])


# Create some dataframes to save the prevalence per ancestry
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to loop through this per ancestry
for (j in ances){

  # I'm basically going to want a lot of data that takes into account the quartile of SES so I'm going to create lasting variables that keep track of that
  data_split = data_df %>% filter(Ances == j)
  
  # I can now use this to pull the main columns of interest
  split_psa = data_split %>% 
    select(contains( c("eid",
                       "prostate_incident",
                       "PSA_Screening")) 
           ) %>% na.omit() %>%  
    # Now group by my 2 variables and see where they land
    group_by(prostate_incident, PSA_Screening) %>% 
    summarize(Count = n()) %>% 
    # Pivot-wider for understanding sake
    pivot_wider(names_from = prostate_incident, values_from = Count) %>% 
    rename(Controls = "0", Cases = "1")
  
    # Add the ancestry and save to overarching dataframe
  summ_df = split_psa %>% 
    mutate(ancestry = j) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .)
  
  }

# I want to make some quick edits for formatting to assist with later formatting
summ_df = summ_df %>% mutate(Control_perc = signif(Controls/(Controls+Cases), digits = 2),
                             Cases_perc = 1-Control_perc) %>% 
                      mutate(Controls = str_c(Controls, " (", Control_perc, ")"),
                             Cases = str_c(Cases, " (", Cases_perc, ")")) %>% 
                      select(ancestry, PSA_Screening, Controls, Cases)

                                )

Antropometric Distributions

The last few variables I have are the bodily measurements that I have, such as age, bmi, and height. Im going to pull those statistics as well as run a t-test to see if there is a significant difference between cases and controls

# Remove non-relevant variables
keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances",
                   "table1") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])



# Pull the relevant variables that I'm trying to summarize
data_anthro = data_df %>% 
  select(Ances,
         contains( c("eid", "prostate_incident")), 
         age_assessment, BMI, Height,
         ) %>% 
  filter(Ances %in% ances )

anthro_descrip = data_anthro %>% na.omit() %>% 
  group_by(Ances, prostate_incident) %>% 
  summarize(across(age_assessment:Height,
                   list(mean = ~ mean(.x, na.rm = T),
                        sd = ~sd(.x, na.rm = T)),
                   .names = "{col}_{.fn}")
  )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Ances'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.
anthro_diff = data_anthro %>% na.omit() %>% 
  group_by(Ances) %>% 
  summarize(across(age_assessment:Height,
                   list(pval = ~t.test(.x ~ prostate_incident)$p.value),
                   .names = "{col}_{.fn}")
  )


# Edit the distribution data to make it easier to add to table
summ_df = anthro_descrip %>% mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ signif(., digits = 3))) %>% 
  mutate(age_assessment = str_c(age_assessment_mean, " (", age_assessment_sd, ")"),
         BMI = str_c(BMI_mean, " (", BMI_sd, ")"),
         Height = str_c(Height_mean, " (", Height_sd, ")")
         ) %>% 
  select(Ances, prostate_incident, age_assessment, BMI, Height)


# Save the summary variables
table1 = table1 %>% list_assign(anthro_dist = summ_df)

Figure 1 - PRS Decile Plot

I will make my first main figure. It will be a decile plot similar to Fig. 1 of Conti et al.2021 where I will calculate the OR of the PRS effect between deciles using the 40-60% scores as a reference.

In order to do this, I will assign every one a decile based on PRS score and then run logit models

Model Generation

# Remove non-relevant variables
keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances",
                   "table1") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])


# Create some dataframes to save the prevalence per ancestry
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to loop through this per ancestry
for (j in ances){
  
  # Print ancestry to benchmark
  print(j)
  
  # Let's pull out the ancestry specific data and set list for models for this ancestry
  data_split = data_df %>% filter(Ances == j)

  # Create new data frame with PRS deciles and setting 40-60 as the reference
  temp_df = data_split %>% drop_na(PRS) %>% 
    mutate(PRS_decile = ntile(PRS, 10) 
           ) %>% 
    # Group middle deciles
    mutate(PRS_decile = if_else(PRS_decile %in% c(5:6),
                                 0, PRS_decile)) %>% 
    # Factor and set levels
    mutate(PRS_decile = factor(PRS_decile, levels = c(0:4,7:10)))
  
  
  # Set the model
  formula = paste0("prostate_incident ~ PRS_decile", 
                   " + age_assessment", str_flatten(str_c("+ PC",1:10))
                   ) %>% as.formula()
      
  model = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = temp_df)
  
      
  # Run the model
  OR = tidy(model, exponentiate = T) %>% 
  rename(OR = estimate) %>% 
  mutate(low95 = exp(log(OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
  up95 = exp(log(OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
  select(-std.error, -statistic) 
  
  # Format the results by pulling relevant data and adding the reference
  results_df = OR[c(2:9),] %>% 
    rbind(tibble(term = "PRS_decile6",
                 OR = 1,
                 p.value = 0,
                 low95 = 1,
                 up95 = 1)) %>% 
    arrange(desc(term == "PRS_decile6"))
  
    # I also want the case/control numbers for all the deciles so let me calculate that and add it to the result
   decile_size <- temp_df %>%
    group_by(PRS_decile) %>%
    mutate(prostate_incident = as.numeric(prostate_incident)) %>%
    summarize(
      control_no = sum(prostate_incident == 1, na.rm = TRUE),
      case_no = sum(prostate_incident == 2, na.rm = TRUE)
    ) %>% 
     mutate(case_control = paste(case_no, control_no, sep = "/"))
  
  # Then add the results and sample size summary data_frame
  summ_df = results_df %>% 
    mutate(ancestry = j,
           case_control = decile_size$case_control) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .)


  
}
[1] "eur"
[1] "afr"
[1] "mix"
[1] "sas"
  

# And now export these models.
summ_df %>%
  write_csv( file = "/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Draft_Figures/Figure1_models_2024.06.21.csv")

Plot generation

Now use the models to actually create Figure 1.

# Edit this df to better plot
`%notin%` = Negate(`%in%`) # Quick helper function

plotting_df = summ_df %>% 
  mutate(term = factor(term, levels = str_c("PRS_decile",c(1:4,6:10)))
  ) 
  
# Create a plot
p1 = plotting_df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = term, y = OR, ymin = low95, ymax = up95, color = ancestry)) +
  geom_pointrange(show.legend = T, position = position_dodge(width = 0.5)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype = "dashed", color = "grey") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("PRS_decile1" = "0-10%", 
                              "PRS_decile2" ="10-20%", 
                              "PRS_decile3" ="20-30%", 
                              "PRS_decile4" ="30-40%",
                              "PRS_decile6" = "40-60%",
                              "PRS_decile7" = "60-70%", 
                              "PRS_decile8" = "70-80%", 
                              "PRS_decile9" = "80-90%", 
                              "PRS_decile10" ="90-100%")) +
  ylim(0,10) +
  labs(y = "Odds Ratio (95% CI)", x = "PRS Deciles") +
  ggtitle(paste0("Prostate Cancer ~ PRS")
          ) +
  theme_minimal()

# Create a second plot that facet's on ancestry as a wrap

# Code to make individual ancestry plots
p_ancestry = plotting_df %>% filter(low95 != 0, ancestry == "eur") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = term, y = OR, ymin = low95, ymax = up95)) +
  geom_pointrange(show.legend = F, position = position_dodge(width = 0.5),
                  colour = "#008080") +

  ggtitle(paste0("Prostate Cancer ~ PRS")

Figure 2 - nSES Forest Plot

The next major plot I want to make is the forst plot of my main SES effects. For this, I will first calculate the effect of the standardized nSES variables and then use some code from online to make a plot

Model Generation

keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# Create some dataframes to save the prevalence per ancestry
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to loop through this per ancestry
for (j in ances){
  
  # Print ancestry to benchmark
  print(j)
  
  # Let's pull out the ancestry specific data and set list for models for this ancestry
  data_split = data_df %>% filter(Ances == j)
  model_results = list()
    
  # Now create a loop that models the variables of interest and then saves them to a list of models
  # Each loop will run a model for total, incidence, and prevalent cases
  for (i in ses_factors){
  
    
    # Create symbol for coding reason
    i = sym(i)
    
    # Calculate the standardized data for the Deprivation index of interest
      temp_df = data_split %>% drop_na(!!i) %>% 
        mutate(Deprivation_z = scale(!!i)[,1]
               )
    
    # Run models of interest
      formula = paste0("prostate_incident ~ Deprivation_z + age_assessment"
                       ) %>% as.formula()
      
      model = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = temp_df)
    
      OR = tidy(model, exponentiate = T) %>% 
        rename(OR = estimate) %>% 
        mutate(low95 = exp(log(OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
               up95 = exp(log(OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
        select(-std.error, -statistic) 
    
      # Pull specific results before saving
      model_results[[i]] <- OR[2,]
      
    
    # Benchmark that this set of model is complete 
    print(i)
  }

  
  # Save the models
  results_df = list_rbind(model_results, names_to = "ses") 
  
  # Remove the term variable (since it's redundant) and then add to summary data_frame
  summ_df = results_df %>% 
    select(-term) %>% 
    mutate(ancestry = j) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .) 

}
  

# And now export these models.
summ_df %>%
  write_csv( file = "/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Draft_Figures/Figure2_models_2024.05.21.csv")


# I also want to try creating a table of these models so I'm going to do some extra formatting and then export that table
table2 = summ_df %>% 
  # Round all the numbers to 3 significant digits for simplicity
  mutate(across(.cols = OR:up95,
                .fns = ~signif(.x, digits = 2),
                .names = "{col}"
                )) %>% 
  
  # First off is combining the low95 and up95 into a single CI column
  mutate(CI = str_c("(", low95, " - ", up95, ")")) %>% 
  
  # Order the columns
  select(ses, ancestry, OR, CI, p.value) %>% 
  
  # And then pivot wier to get all the ancestries as columns per index
  pivot_wider(names_from = ancestry, 
              values_from = c(OR, CI, p.value),
              names_vary = "slowest",
              names_glue = "{ancestry}_{.value}")

# And now export this table
table2 %>% 
  write_csv(file = "/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Draft_Figures/Table2_models_2024.05.21.csv")

Calculate the ORs for the different stratified PSA status


keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])



# Create some dataframes to save the prevalence per ancestry
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to calculate the p-value for the difference in the models so I need to save the estimate and SE
estimate_df = tibble()


# I also want to loop between the PSA status
for (j in 0:1){
  
  # Print ancestry to benchmark
  print(j)
  
  # Let's pull out the ancestry specific data and set list for models for this ancestry
  data_split = data_df %>% filter(Ances == "eur",
                                  PSA_Screening == j)
  model_results = list()
  estimate_results = list()
    
  # Now create a loop that models the variables of interest and then saves them to a list of models
  # Each loop will run a model for total, incidence, and prevalent cases
  for (i in ses_factors){
  
    
    # Create symbol for coding reason
    i = sym(i)
    
    # Calculate the standardized data for the Deprivation index of interest
      temp_df = data_split %>% drop_na(!!i) %>% 
        mutate(Deprivation_z = scale(!!i)[,1]
               )
    
    # Run models of interest
      formula = paste0("prostate_incident ~ Deprivation_z + age_assessment"
                       ) %>% as.formula()
      
      model = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = temp_df)
    
      OR = tidy(model, exponentiate = T) %>% 
        rename(OR = estimate) %>% 
        mutate(low95 = exp(log(OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
               up95 = exp(log(OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
        select(-std.error, -statistic) 
    
      # Pull specific results before saving
      model_results[[i]] <- OR[2,]
      
      # Pull estimates befores saving
      estimate_results[[i]] = tidy(model, exponentiate = F) %>% 
        select(term, estimate, std.error) %>% .[2,]
    
    # Benchmark that this set of model is complete 
    print(i)
  }

  
  # Save the models
  results_df = list_rbind(model_results, names_to = "ses") 
  
  # Remove the term variable (since it's redundant) and then add to summary data_frame
  summ_df = results_df %>% 
    select(-term) %>% 
    mutate(PSA_Screening = factor(j, levels = c(0,1))) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .) 

  
  # Perform a similar process for the estimates where I collect them and format them
  estimate_df = list_rbind(estimate_results, names_to = "ses") %>% 
    select(-term) %>% 
    mutate(PSA_Screening = factor(j, levels = c(0,1))) %>% 
    rbind(estimate_df,.)
  
}

# Along with the models, I want to see if there is a formal difference in the ln(OR)'s per deprivation index
difference_df = tibble()
for (i in ses_factors){
  
  # Pull the index specific log odds and se's
  z_df = estimate_df %>% filter(ses == i)
  ln_odds = z_df %>% pull(estimate) 
  se_ln_odds = z_df %>% pull(std.error)
  
  # Calc the z-score and pvalue
  z_value = (ln_odds[1] - ln_odds[2]) / sqrt(se_ln_odds[1]^2 + se_ln_odds[2]^2)
  p_val = abs(z_value) %>% pnorm(q = ., lower.tail=FALSE) %>% '*'(2)
  
  # Add to final table
  z_df = z_df %>% mutate(p.val = p_val) %>% 
    select(-c(estimate, std.error, PSA_Screening)) %>% .[1,]
  difference_df = rbind(difference_df, z_df)
  
}

# Add on these p-values to the original table 
summ_df = left_join(summ_df, difference_df) %>% 
  rename(diff_p.val = p.val) %>% 
  mutate(diff_p.val = round(diff_p.val,3))
Joining with `by = join_by(ses)`

# Change the name of Housing to "Housing/Services" to make the results more obvious and then make it a factor
plot_df <- summ_df %>%
  mutate(ses = ifelse(ses == "Housing", "Housing/Services", ses)) %>%
  mutate(ses = factor(ses, levels = c("Income", "Employment", "Education", "Environment", "Health", "Housing/Services", "Crime", "IMD", "Townsend"))) %>%
  mutate(shading_group = as.factor((as.numeric(ses) %% 2) == 0))

# Build middle of volcano plot
p = plot_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = fct_rev(ses))) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "top") +
  
  # Add alternating shading
  geom_rect(aes(xmin = -Inf, xmax = Inf, ymin = as.numeric(ses) - 0.5, ymax = as.numeric(ses) + 0.5, fill = shading_group), alpha = 0.1) +

  geom_pointrange(aes(x = OR, xmin = low95, xmax = up95, color = PSA_Screening), 
                  show.legend = TRUE,
                  shape = 15,
                  position = position_dodge(width = 0.5)) + 
  geom_text(aes(x = 1.09, y = as.numeric(ses), label = round(diff_p.val, 3)),
            hjust = 0, fontface = "bold") +
  
  # Change the legend labels
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("0" = "red", "1" = "blue"),
    labels = c("Never screened", "At least one screening"),
    name = "Ever PSA Screened?"  # Change legend title
  ) +
  
  # Change fill scale to alternate between gray and white
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "gray70", "FALSE" = "white")) +
  
  # Change axis sizes
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 11, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 11, face = "bold")) + 

  # Add x-intercept and axis titles
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Odds Ratio", y = "") +
  
  # Add space
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0.5, 9.5), xlim = c(0.85, 1.1)) +
  
  # Add note about the effect
  annotate("text", x = 1.096, y = 9.71, label = "P-value", fontface = "bold") +
  
  # Remove the legend for shading
  guides(fill = FALSE)

# Remove non-relevant variables
keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances",
                   "table1") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])


# Create some dataframes to save the results
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to loop through this per deprivation and strata
for (i in ses_factors){
  
  # Print deprivation index to benchmark
  print(i)
  
  # Create symbol for coding reason
  i = sym(i)
    
  # Calculate quartiles for deprivation of interest (also only pull EUR)
  temp_df = data_df %>% filter(Ances == "eur") %>% 
    drop_na(!!i) %>% mutate(Deprivation_Quartiles = ntile(!!i, 4)
                            )
  # Have place to save models
  model_results = list()
  
  # Loop through the deprivation quartiles
  for (j in 1:4){
  
    # Stratify to only data in the quartile
    model_data = temp_df %>% filter(Deprivation_Quartiles == j)
    
    # Set the model
    formula = paste0("prostate_incident ~ PRS_z + age_assessment", 
                     str_flatten(str_c("+ PC",1:10))
                     ) %>% as.formula()
      
    model = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = model_data)
    
      
    # Tidy the model results
    OR = tidy(model, exponentiate = T) %>% 
    rename(PRS_OR = estimate) %>% 
    mutate(low95 = exp(log(PRS_OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
    up95 = exp(log(PRS_OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
    select(-std.error, -statistic) 
    
    # Format the results by pulling relevant data and adding the reference
    model_results[[j]] <- OR[2,]
    
    # Benchmark that this set of model is complete 
    print(j)
    
  }
  
  # Save the models
  results_df = list_rbind(model_results, names_to = "quartile") 
  
  # I also want to run a heterogeneity cochran's q-test to see if any of the effects are different
  meta_test = metagen(TE = log(PRS_OR), 
                      lower = log(low95), upper = log(up95),
                      pval = rep(0.05,4),
                      studlab = 1:4,
                      data = results_df)
  results_df = results_df %>% 
    mutate(het_p.val = round(meta_test$pval.Q,
                             3)
           )
  
  
  # Remove the term variable (since it's redundant) and then add to summary data_frame
  summ_df = results_df %>% 
    select(-term) %>% 
    mutate(ses = as.character(i)
           ) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .) %>% 
    select(ses, !ses)
  
}

# I also want to try creating a table of these models so I'm going to do some extra formatting and then export that table
table4 = summ_df %>% 
  # Round all the numbers to 3 significant digits for simplicity
  mutate(across(.cols = PRS_OR:het_p.val,
                .fns = ~signif(.x, digits = 3),
                .names = "{col}"
                )) %>% 
  
  # First off is combining the low95 and up95 into a single CI column
  mutate(CI = str_c("(", low95, " - ", up95, ")")) %>% 
  
  # Order the columns
  select(ses:p.value, het_p.val:CI) %>% 
  
  # And then pivot wier to get all the ancestries as columns per index
  pivot_wider(names_from = quartile, 
              values_from = c(PRS_OR, CI, p.value),
              names_vary = "slowest",
              names_glue = "{quartile}_{.value}") %>% 
  
  # Reorder columns for simplicity
  select(!het_p.val, het_p.val)

# And now export this table
table4 %>% 
  write_csv(file = "/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Draft_Figures/Table4_models_2024.05.21.csv")

This next area for all the extra little figures that I want to generate that people have mentioned that I need to make

Supp 1 - Continuous PRS risk

Instead of the decile plot, I want to run an analysis where I treat PRS score as continuous scores. I will need to make sure to standardize the PRS scores by ancestry prior to modeling

I want to repeat this specific analysis for the PRS269 and PRScsx scores. To do that, I need to process them the same way as the other data before hand. Let me note those steps

Process PRS269 and PRS-CSx data

# Remove non-relevant variables
keep_variables = c("data_df", "data_df_PRS269", "data_df_PRScsx", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances",
                   "table1") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# Processing PRS269 data
data_df_PRS269 = fread("/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Composite_DataFiles/composite_data_PRS269_2024.05.16.csv") %>% 
  #First, I want a variable that counts any prostate cancer as case and no cancer at all as the control. 
  # If no prostate cancer, but other cancer, then that is NA
  mutate(prostate_case = ifelse(prostate == 1, 1,
                         ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                         ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                         ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0)))
                         )
                                 
         ) %>% 
  # I also want to include a measure of incident cancer
  mutate(prostate_incident = if_else(prostate_incid_any == 1, 1,
                                     if_else(prostate_incid_any == 0 & prostate == 1, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                                     ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0))))
                                     )
         ) %>% 
  # I also want prevalent cancer
  mutate(prostate_prevalent =  if_else(prostate_incid_any == 1, NA,
                                     if_else(prostate_incid_any == 0 & prostate == 1, 1,
                                     ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                                     ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0))))
                                     )
         ) %>% 
  # Make all of these factors
  mutate(prostate_case = as.factor(prostate_case),
         prostate_incident = as.factor(prostate_incident),
         prostate_prevalent = as.factor(prostate_prevalent)) %>% 
  # I want to remove non-UK assessment centers
  filter(Assessment_Centre %notin% c(11023, 11022, 11003, 11005, 11004)
  ) %>% 
  # I also want assessment center and the smoking to be a factor
  mutate(Assessment_Centre = as.factor(Assessment_Centre)) %>% 
  
  # And rename Townsend_Index to just Townsend for clarity
  rename(Townsend = Townsend_Index)

# -- -- -- -- -- -- -- -- -- -- -- --
# Process PRS-CSX data
data_df_PRScsx = fread("/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Composite_DataFiles/composite_data_PRScsx_2024.05.16.csv") %>% 
  #First, I want a variable that counts any prostate cancer as case and no cancer at all as the control. 
  # If no prostate cancer, but other cancer, then that is NA
  mutate(prostate_case = ifelse(prostate == 1, 1,
                         ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                         ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                         ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0)))
                         )
                                 
         ) %>% 
  # I also want to include a measure of incident cancer
  mutate(prostate_incident = if_else(prostate_incid_any == 1, 1,
                                     if_else(prostate_incid_any == 0 & prostate == 1, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                                     ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0))))
                                     )
         ) %>% 
  # I also want prevalent cancer
  mutate(prostate_prevalent =  if_else(prostate_incid_any == 1, NA,
                                     if_else(prostate_incid_any == 0 & prostate == 1, 1,
                                     ifelse(case == 1 & prostate == 0 & othskin == 0, NA,
                                     ifelse(case == 0, 0,
                                     ifelse(prostate == 0 & othskin == 1 & case == 1, 0, 0))))
                                     )
         ) %>% 
  # Make all of these factors
  mutate(prostate_case = as.factor(prostate_case),
         prostate_incident = as.factor(prostate_incident),
         prostate_prevalent = as.factor(prostate_prevalent)) %>% 
  # I want to remove non-UK assessment centers
  filter(Assessment_Centre %notin% c(11023, 11022, 11003, 11005, 11004)
  ) %>% 
  # I also want assessment center and the smoking to be a factor
  mutate(Assessment_Centre = as.factor(Assessment_Centre)) %>% 
  
  # And rename Townsend_Index to just Townsend for clarity
  rename(Townsend = Townsend_Index)

Modeling risk for 3 PRS models

# Remove non-relevant variables
keep_variables = c("data_df", "data_df_PRS269", "data_df_PRScsx", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances",
                   "table1") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# Create some dataframes to save the results
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to loop through this per ancestry and I'm actually going to use this to run through all the scores I have
for (j in ances){
  
  # Print ancestry to benchmark
  print(j)
  
  # Let's pull out the ancestry specific data and set list for models for this ancestry
  data_split_PRS451 = data_df %>% filter(Ances == j) %>% drop_na(PRS) 
  data_split_PRS269 = data_df_PRS269 %>% filter(Ances == j) %>%  drop_na(PRS) 
  data_split_PRScsx = data_df_PRScsx %>% filter(Ances == j) %>% drop_na(PRS) 
  
  # Set the model
  formula = paste0("prostate_incident ~ PRS_z", 
                   " + age_assessment", str_flatten(str_c("+ PC",1:10))
                   ) %>% as.formula()
  
  # Run the model    
  model_451 = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = data_split_PRS451)
  model_269 = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = data_split_PRS269)
  model_csx = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = data_split_PRScsx)
  
      
  # Organize the model reulst
  OR_451 = tidy(model_451, exponentiate = T) %>% 
    rename(OR = estimate) %>% 
    mutate(PRS = "PRS_451") %>% 
    mutate(low95 = exp(log(OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
           up95 = exp(log(OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
    select(PRS, OR, p.value, low95, up95) %>% .[2,]
  
  OR_269 = tidy(model_269, exponentiate = T) %>% 
    rename(OR = estimate) %>% 
    mutate(PRS = "PRS_269") %>% 
    mutate(low95 = exp(log(OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
           up95 = exp(log(OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
    select(PRS, OR, p.value, low95, up95) %>% .[2,]
  
  OR_csx = tidy(model_csx, exponentiate = T) %>% 
    rename(OR = estimate) %>% 
    mutate(OR = 1/OR) %>% # I messed up the effect allele when calculating the score so I have the inverse effect
    mutate(PRS = "PRS_csx") %>% 
    mutate(low95 = exp(log(OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
           up95 = exp(log(OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
    select(PRS, OR, p.value, low95, up95) %>% .[2,]
  
  # Merge the separate model results
  results_df = rbind(OR_451, OR_269, OR_csx)
  
  # Then add to summary data_frame
  summ_df = results_df %>% 
    mutate(ancestry = j) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .)

}

Supp 2 - Simple interaction

In order to take advantage of non-European data, I will run simple nSES*PRS logistic regression models to see the non-sig interactions across ancestries

keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# Create some dataframes to save the prevalence per ancestry
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to loop through this per ancestry
for (j in ances){
  
  # Print ancestry to benchmark
  print(j)
  
  # Let's pull out the ancestry specific data and set list for models for this ancestry
  data_split = data_df %>% filter(Ances == j)
  model_results = list()
    
  # Now create a loop that models the variables of interest and then saves them to a list of models
  # Each loop will run a model for total, incidence, and prevalent cases
  for (i in ses_factors){
  
    
    # Create symbol for coding reason
    i = sym(i)
    
    # Calculate the standardized data for the Deprivation index of interest
      temp_df = data_split %>% drop_na(!!i) %>% 
        mutate(Deprivation_z = scale(!!i)[,1]
               )
    
    # Run models of interest
      formula = paste0("prostate_incident ~ Deprivation_z + PRS_z + Deprivation_z*PRS_z", 
                   " + age_assessment", str_flatten(str_c("+ PC",1:10))
                   ) %>% as.formula()
      
      model = logistic_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = temp_df)
    
      OR = tidy(model, exponentiate = T) %>% 
        rename(OR = estimate) %>% 
        mutate(low95 = exp(log(OR) - 1.96*std.error), 
               up95 = exp(log(OR) + 1.96*std.error)) %>% 
        select(-std.error, -statistic) 
    
      # Pull specific results before saving
      model_results[[i]] <- OR[c(2,3,15),]
      
    
    # Benchmark that this set of model is complete 
    print(i)
  }

  
  # Save the models
  results_df = list_rbind(model_results, names_to = "ses") 
  
  # Remove the term variable (since it's redundant) and then add to summary data_frame
  summ_df = results_df %>% 
    mutate(ancestry = j) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .) 

}

Supp 3 - Sensitivity Analyses (PSA Screening & Healthcare Utilization)

I will use this next section to start incorporating some of the models/questions I have about PSA Screening and healthcare utilization. I will specificially make 4 sets of models - PCa ~ nSES + PSA Screening - PCa ~ nSES + Healthcare Utilization - PCA ~ nSES + PSA + Healthcare - corr(PSA Screening, Healthcare Utilization, nSES)

PCa ~ nSES + PSA Screening

I want to include PSA Screening as a covariate in my nSES to see how the effect changes

keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# Create some dataframes to save the prevalence per ancestry

  # Now create a loop that models the variables of interest and then saves them to a list of models

Supp 4 - Associations with covariates

In the previous suppliments, I model PSA Screening and Healthcare utilization as covariates with nSES. I want to see the association of these covariates with nSES independently. I also want to see their correlation with each other the nSES variables

This will be 3 models - PSA ~ nSES - Healthcare ~ nSES ~ Correlations w/ PSAHealthcarenSES

PSA ~ nSES

      # Save the predictions
      pred_list[[i]] = model %>% predict(temp_df)

Healthcare ~ nSES

I will use my new variable that has counted the number of GP visits in the year prior to recruitments I will first use the GP visits as the outcome

keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# Create some dataframes to save the prevalence per ancestry
summ_df = tibble()

# I also want to loop through this per ancestry
for (j in ances){
  
  # Print ancestry to benchmark
  print(j)
  
  # Let's pull out the ancestry specific data and set list for models for this ancestry
  data_split = data_df %>% filter(Ances == j)
  model_results = list()
    
  # Now create a loop that models the variables of interest and then saves them to a list of models
  # Each loop will run a model for total, incidence, and prevalent cases
  for (i in ses_factors){
  
    
    # Create symbol for coding reason
    i = sym(i)
    
    # Calculate the standardized data for the Deprivation index of interest
      temp_df = data_split %>% drop_na(!!i) %>% 
        mutate(Deprivation_z = scale(!!i)[,1]
               )
    
    # Run models of interest
      formula = paste0("no_visits ~ Deprivation_z + age_assessment"
                       ) %>% as.formula()
      
      model = linear_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = temp_df)
    
      results = tidy(model) %>% 
        mutate(low95 = estimate - 1.96*std.error, 
               up95 = estimate + 1.96*std.error) %>% 
        select(-std.error, -statistic) 
    
      # Pull specific results before saving
      model_results[[i]] <- results[2,]
      
    
    # Benchmark that this set of model is complete 
    print(i)
  }

  
  # Save the models
  results_df = list_rbind(model_results, names_to = "ses") 
  
  # Remove the term variable (since it's redundant) and then add to summary data_frame
  summ_df = results_df %>% 
    select(-term) %>% 
    mutate(ancestry = j) %>% 
    rbind(summ_df, .) 

}

Since thia analysis is a bit wonky. I want to try modeling the results to see if they make sense. I am going to model it in the original standard, model it with the outcome as a binary, and with # of visits as a inverse-normal

# I'm just going to try modeling IMD since the rest are probably going to be similar
# I need to quickly rerun the model to get the predictions
temp_df = data_df %>% filter(Ances == "eur") %>% drop_na(IMD) %>% drop_na(no_visits) %>% 
        mutate(Deprivation_z = scale(IMD)[,1],
               int_visits = qnorm((rank(no_visits, ties.method = "average") - 0.5)/
                                     length(no_visits)
                                    ),
               binary_visits = ifelse(no_visits == 1, 0, 1)
               )

formula = paste0("no_visits ~ Deprivation_z + age_assessment"
                       ) %>% as.formula()
model = linear_reg() %>% fit(formula, data = temp_df)

# I need to predict # of visits from the variable and then save it
plot_df = model %>% predict(temp_df) %>% bind_cols(temp_df, .) %>% 
  mutate(IMD_z = scale(IMD)[,1]) %>% select(eid, IMD, IMD_z, no_visits, .pred)

# Now plot
ggplot(plot_df, aes(x = IMD_z, y = no_visits)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = .pred), color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Linear Regression: IMD vs Clinical Visits",
       x = "Standardized IMD",
       y = "Clinical Visits") +
  theme_minimal()

Supp 5 - Exclusion Criteria Differences

Throughout my analyses, I have removed people that didnt have - genetic data - IMD data, or - PCa data More importantly I removed people without non-melanoma skin cancer and no PSA screening data

I am potentially reducing my power with all this reduction. Let me check how much people I removed with these steps

# Reset the environment
keep_variables = c("data_df", "keep_variables", "ses_factors", "ances") 
rm(list = ls()[!(ls() %in% keep_variables)])

# Load the raw data
data_raw = fread("/labs/jswitte/Projects/jjudd5/SES.PRS_Project/Composite_DataFiles/composite_data_2024.04.16.csv")

# First, how many men with genetic data (which is the number of non-empty PRS rows)
men_with_genetic = data_raw %>% select(eid, PRS) %>% drop_na() %>% nrow()
men_with_genetic

# How many people without IMD data (count IMD NAs)
men_wo_deprivation = data_raw %>% filter(is.na(IMD)) %>% nrow()
men_wo_deprivation

# Men without cancer data
men_wo_pca = data_raw %>% filter(is.na(prostate)) %>% nrow()
men_wo_pca

# Men without psa screening data
men_wo_psa = data_raw %>% filter(is.na(PSA_Screening)) %>% nrow()
men_wo_psa
